---
import SiteLayout from "../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Wells Fargo & Company (WFC) Intrinsic Value",
  description: "An independent intrinsic value estimate for Wells Fargo & Company (WFC) using a two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF) model.",
  category: "study",
  published: "2026-03-18"
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": meta.title,
  "description": meta.description,
  "datePublished": meta.published,
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "Gemini 2.5 Pro"
  }
};

// Current market data
const currentPrice = 76.60;
const sharesOutstanding = 3242; // in millions (Basic Shares)
const totalCash = 174210; // in millions
const totalDebt = 174712; // in millions
const netDebt = totalDebt - totalCash; // 502 million

// The cyclical nature of bank free cash flow makes a single year an unreliable starting point.
// WFC 5-year FCF history: -19001, 3035, 40358, 27048, -11525.
// Average FCF over the cycle: 7983 million.
const baseFCF = 7983;

// Growth assumptions
const wacc = 0.095; // 9.5% discount rate (WACC / Cost of Equity for Banks)
const shortTermGrowthRate = 0.03; // 3.0% Years 1-5
const terminalGrowthRate = 0.025; // 2.5% Terminal Growth (Inflation/GDP match)

// DCF Calculation
const projectedFCF = [];
const presentValues = [];
let cumulativePV = 0;

for (let year = 1; year <= 5; year++) {
  const fcf = baseFCF * Math.pow(1 + shortTermGrowthRate, year);
  projectedFCF.push(fcf);

  const pv = fcf / Math.pow(1 + wacc, year);
  presentValues.push(pv);
  cumulativePV += pv;
}

// Terminal Value
const year5FCF = projectedFCF[4];
const terminalValue = (year5FCF * (1 + terminalGrowthRate)) / (wacc - terminalGrowthRate);
const presentValueOfTerminalValue = terminalValue / Math.pow(1 + wacc, 5);

// Enterprise & Equity Value
const enterpriseValue = cumulativePV + presentValueOfTerminalValue;
const equityValue = enterpriseValue - netDebt;
const intrinsicValuePerShare = equityValue / sharesOutstanding;

// Formatting functions
const formatCurrency = (val) => new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD', minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 }).format(val);
const formatMillions = (val) => new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD', minimumFractionDigits: 0, maximumFractionDigits: 0 }).format(val) + "M";
const formatPercent = (val) => (val * 100).toFixed(1) + "%";

// Verdict logic
const upside = (intrinsicValuePerShare - currentPrice) / currentPrice;
const isUndervalued = intrinsicValuePerShare > currentPrice;
const verdictText = isUndervalued ? "Undervalued" : "Overvalued";
const verdictColor = isUndervalued ? "#22c55e" : "#ef4444"; // Green or Red

// Sensitivity Matrix
const waccSteps = [-0.01, -0.005, 0, 0.005, 0.01];
const tgrSteps = [-0.005, -0.0025, 0, 0.0025, 0.005];

const sensitivityMatrix = tgrSteps.map(tgrOffset => {
  const currentTgr = terminalGrowthRate + tgrOffset;
  return {
    tgr: currentTgr,
    values: waccSteps.map(waccOffset => {
      const currentWacc = wacc + waccOffset;
      const tv = (year5FCF * (1 + currentTgr)) / (currentWacc - currentTgr);
      const pvTv = tv / Math.pow(1 + currentWacc, 5);

      let tempCumPV = 0;
      for (let year = 1; year <= 5; year++) {
        tempCumPV += projectedFCF[year - 1] / Math.pow(1 + currentWacc, year);
      }

      const ev = tempCumPV + pvTv;
      const eq = ev - netDebt;
      return eq / sharesOutstanding;
    })
  };
});
---
<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/wells-fargo-intrinsic-value" schema={schema}>
  <div class="container">
    <header class="page-header">
      <div class="badge">Study</div>
      <h1>{meta.title}</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Compiled by Gemini 2.5 Pro</p>
      <p class="summary">{meta.description}</p>
    </header>

    <section class="verdict-section">
      <div class="verdict-card">
        <h2>Intrinsic Value Estimate</h2>
        <div class="value-display">
          <span class="intrinsic-value">{formatCurrency(intrinsicValuePerShare)}</span>
          <span class="currency">USD</span>
        </div>
        <div class="current-price-row">
          <span>Current Price: <strong>{formatCurrency(currentPrice)}</strong></span>
          <span class="upside" style={`color: ${verdictColor}`}>
            {verdictText} ({formatPercent(Math.abs(upside))})
          </span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="methodology-section">
      <h2>Methodology & Assumptions</h2>
      <p>Wells Fargo is a mature, cyclical banking institution. Because Free Cash Flow (FCF) for banks can swing wildly due to changes in working capital, loan originations, and regulatory reserve requirements, relying on a single trailing twelve-month FCF figure is highly misleading. WFC's last five years of FCF are: -$19B, $3B, $40B, $27B, and -$11B.</p>

      <p>I am using a normalized/average Free Cash Flow over the cycle approach for the base year to smooth out cyclical distortions, combined with a standard two-stage Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) model.</p>

      <div class="assumptions-grid">
        <div class="assumption-card">
          <h3>Base Free Cash Flow</h3>
          <div class="assumption-value">{formatMillions(baseFCF)}</div>
          <p>Calculated as the arithmetic mean of WFC's Free Cash Flow over the previous five fiscal years. This provides a stabilized foundation representing the bank's true cash-generating power across credit cycles.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="assumption-card">
          <h3>FCF Growth Rate (Y1-5)</h3>
          <div class="assumption-value">{formatPercent(shortTermGrowthRate)}</div>
          <p>A conservative 3.0% growth rate reflecting long-term nominal GDP growth and WFC's stabilized position post-asset cap controversies. Banks generally grow alongside the broader economy.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="assumption-card">
          <h3>Discount Rate (WACC)</h3>
          <div class="assumption-value">{formatPercent(wacc)}</div>
          <p>Set at 9.5%. Utilizing CAPM with a 10-Year Treasury yield of 4.18%, a beta of ~1.1, and an equity risk premium of 5.0%, adjusting slightly upwards to account for persistent regulatory overhang.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="assumption-card">
          <h3>Terminal Growth Rate</h3>
          <div class="assumption-value">{formatPercent(terminalGrowthRate)}</div>
          <p>Set at 2.5%. A bank cannot outgrow the global economy in perpetuity. This aligns with long-run inflation expectations and sustainable nominal GDP expansion.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="projections-section">
      <h2>Stage 1: FCF Projections (Years 1-5)</h2>
      <div class="table-container">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Year</th>
              <th>Projected FCF</th>
              <th>Discount Factor (9.5%)</th>
              <th>Present Value</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {projectedFCF.map((fcf, index) => (
              <tr>
                <td>Year {index + 1}</td>
                <td class="numeric">{formatMillions(fcf)}</td>
                <td class="numeric">{(1 / Math.pow(1 + wacc, index + 1)).toFixed(3)}</td>
                <td class="numeric">{formatMillions(presentValues[index])}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
            <tr class="total-row">
              <td colspan="3">Cumulative Present Value (Stage 1)</td>
              <td class="numeric">{formatMillions(cumulativePV)}</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="valuation-section">
      <h2>Stage 2: Terminal Value & Final Valuation</h2>
      <div class="table-container">
        <table>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Year 5 FCF</td>
              <td class="numeric">{formatMillions(year5FCF)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Terminal Value (Gordon Growth Method)</td>
              <td class="numeric">{formatMillions(terminalValue)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Present Value of Terminal Value</td>
              <td class="numeric">{formatMillions(presentValueOfTerminalValue)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="highlight-row">
              <td><strong>Implied Enterprise Value</strong></td>
              <td class="numeric"><strong>{formatMillions(enterpriseValue)}</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Less: Net Debt (Total Debt - Cash)</td>
              <td class="numeric">{formatMillions(netDebt)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="highlight-row">
              <td><strong>Implied Equity Value</strong></td>
              <td class="numeric"><strong>{formatMillions(equityValue)}</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Shares Outstanding (Basic)</td>
              <td class="numeric">{sharesOutstanding}M</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="final-row">
              <td><strong>Intrinsic Value Per Share</strong></td>
              <td class="numeric" style={`color: ${verdictColor}`}><strong>{formatCurrency(intrinsicValuePerShare)}</strong></td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sensitivity-section">
      <h2>Sensitivity Matrix</h2>
      <p>Intrinsic value per share across different Terminal Growth Rate and WACC combinations.</p>
      <div class="table-container">
        <table class="matrix-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>TGR \ WACC</th>
              {waccSteps.map(w => <th>{formatPercent(wacc + w)}</th>)}
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {sensitivityMatrix.map(row => (
              <tr>
                <th>{formatPercent(row.tgr)}</th>
                {row.values.map(val => (
                  <td class="numeric" style={val > currentPrice ? `color: #22c55e` : `color: #ef4444`}>
                    {formatCurrency(val)}
                  </td>
                ))}
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="risks-section">
      <h2>Key Risks to This Valuation</h2>
      <ul class="risk-list">
        <li><strong>Regulatory Asset Cap:</strong> WFC has operated under an unprecedented Federal Reserve asset cap since 2018. If this cap remains in place longer than the market anticipates, the 3.0% short-term growth assumption will be highly optimistic.</li>
        <li><strong>Net Interest Margin (NIM) Compression:</strong> As interest rates potentially fall, WFC's net interest income could contract, suppressing normalized cash flow below the historic $7.98B average.</li>
        <li><strong>Commercial Real Estate (CRE) Exposure:</strong> WFC holds a substantial portfolio of commercial real estate loans, particularly office properties, which remain vulnerable to elevated default rates.</li>
        <li><strong>Cyclical Downturns:</strong> A severe macroeconomic recession would drive up credit loss provisions, collapsing free cash flow and invalidating the steady growth trajectory modeled here.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>Why is Wells Fargo's Free Cash Flow negative in some years?</summary>
        <p>For banks, Free Cash Flow is heavily influenced by changes in operational assets and liabilities—specifically loan originations and deposits. When a bank aggressively originates new loans, cash outflows spike, resulting in negative FCF for that period, even if the bank reports strong net income. This is why a normalized, multi-year average is preferred for bank DCF models.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How does the asset cap affect the DCF model?</summary>
        <p>The Federal Reserve's asset cap prevents Wells Fargo from growing its balance sheet. In a DCF, this primarily suppresses the short-term Free Cash Flow growth rate. The conservative 3.0% growth rate modeled here assumes limited, highly-optimized loan growth and a primary focus on cost-cutting and efficiency rather than aggressive balance sheet expansion.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why use CAPM for a bank's Cost of Equity?</summary>
        <p>The Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM) incorporates the risk-free rate (10-Year Treasury) and the equity risk premium, adjusted by the stock's volatility relative to the market (Beta). Given banks' exposure to systemic risk, interest rate risk, and regulatory risk, an elevated cost of equity (like 9.5%) is necessary to adequately discount future, uncertain cash flows.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

    <footer class="disclaimer">
      <h3>Disclaimer</h3>
      <p>This discounted cash flow analysis was algorithmically generated by Gemini 2.5 Pro as an educational study and demonstration of financial modeling techniques. It does not constitute financial advice, an investment recommendation, or an endorsement of Wells Fargo & Company. The assumptions utilized (WACC, Growth Rates, Normalized FCF) are subjective estimates. Actual future performance will vary, potentially significantly. Always consult a certified financial planner or conduct your own extensive due diligence prior to investing.</p>
    </footer>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>

